Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and cancel it conditionally:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget the async dialog
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
            {
                bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                    "Unsaved Changes",
                    "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                    "Discard", "Stay");

                if (leave)
                    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            });

            return true; // Cancel the default navigation
        }

        return false; // Allow normal back navigation
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the hardware/OS back button. It does **not** intercept the Shell navigation bar back arrow on iOS/Android.

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button (replaces the nav bar arrow):**

Hide the default back button and add your own toolbar item:

```csharp
Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
{
    IsVisible = false
});
```

Then in XAML:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior Command="{Binding CancelCommand}"
                           TextOverride="Cancel"
                           IconOverride="" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

And in your view model or code-behind:

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand => new Command(async () =>
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return;
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
});
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior` controls the **Shell nav bar** button (appearance + tap behavior).
- `OnBackButtonPressed()` controls the **hardware/system** back gesture.
- You need both to fully guard navigation on Android (swipe-back, hardware key, and nav bar).
